    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1968-10-25T05:54:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1968-10-25T05:54:00-05:00" n="120"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d120">
                <head>120. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in France</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d120fn1">Source: National Archives and Records
                        Administration, <gloss target="#t_RG1">RG</gloss> 59, <gloss
                            target="#t_AIM1">A/IM</gloss> Files: Lot 93 D 82, <gloss
                            target="#t_HARVAN1">HARVAN</gloss>-(Incoming)-October 1968. Secret;
                        Immediate; <gloss target="#t_Nodis1">Nodis</gloss>/<gloss
                            target="#t_HARVAN1">HARVAN</gloss> Double Plus. Received at 7:17 a.m.
                        Repeated to Saigon.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Paris</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1968-10-25T10:54:00+00:00">October 25, 1968,
                        1054Z</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>22926/<gloss target="#t_Delto1">Delto</gloss> 878. Ref: State 260990.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d120fn2">
                        <ref target="#d118">Document 118</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Following comments are keyed to numbering of State 260990 on procedural
                        problems, and take into account state of play with <gloss target="#t_DRV1"
                            >DRV</gloss>, as appropriate. <pb facs="0368" n="334" xml:id="pg_334"/>
                        <list>
                            <label>(A)</label>
                            <item>Flags and nameplates. We have been pressing same line with
                                    <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName> as contained <gloss
                                    target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss>. May we assume on the basis
                                of Saigon 41093<note n="3" xml:id="d120fn3">In telegram 41093 from
                                    Saigon October 24, the Embassy reported on a meeting between
                                        <persName corresp="#p_TCT1">Thanh</persName> and <persName
                                        corresp="#p_BSR1">Berger</persName> and <persName
                                        corresp="#p_HMF1">Herz</persName> in which they found
                                        <persName corresp="#p_TCT1">Thanh</persName> generally
                                    agreeable on procedural issues. (<persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                                        >Johnson</persName> Library, National Security File, Country
                                    File, Vietnam, Memos to the President/Bombing Halt Decisions,
                                    Vol. II)</note> that <gloss target="#t_GVN1">GVN</gloss> will
                                change <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName>’s
                                instructions?</item>
                            <label>(B)</label>
                            <item>Name for the conference. With both <persName corresp="#p_XTC1"
                                    >Thuy</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName>,
                                as reported in Paris 22914,<note n="4" xml:id="d120fn4">See <ref
                                        target="#d116fn2">footnote 2, Document 116</ref>.</note>
                                para 17, and Paris 22912,<note n="5" xml:id="d120fn5">In telegram
                                        22912/<gloss target="#t_Delto1">Delto</gloss> 875 from
                                    Paris, October 24, the Embassy reported on a meeting between
                                        <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName> and <persName
                                        corresp="#p_HPC1">Habib</persName> on procedural matters.
                                        (<persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> Library,
                                    National Security File, Country File, Vietnam, <gloss
                                        target="#t_HARVAN1">HARVAN</gloss>/DOUBLE PLUS, Vol.
                                    III)</note> respectively we have talked of the next phase as
                                “meetings”. Moreover, in accordance with instructions, we used the
                                word “meetings” in our draft minute (Paris 22914, para 36). The
                                    <gloss target="#t_DRV1">DRV</gloss> has agreed to the term
                                “meetings”, and we believe it wise to stick to it rather than to use
                                “talks.” Thus we believe name would best be “Paris meetings” or
                                “Paris meetings on Viet-Nam”. Final agreement, of course, will be
                                part of negotiations on procedure.</item>
                            <label>(C)</label>
                            <item>Order of entrance. We concur in <gloss target="#t_reftel1"
                                    >reftel</gloss> positions.</item>
                            <label>(D)</label>
                            <item>Chairmanship of delegation. Concur with <gloss target="#t_reftel1"
                                    >reftel</gloss>.</item>
                            <label>(E)</label>
                            <item>Opening statement. Concur <gloss target="#t_reftel1"
                                    >reftel</gloss>. Please note also the question of the order of
                                speaking, on which we want to remain flexible until later. This will
                                be a question of tactics which we can decide here. Embassy Saigon
                                should not agree on this without reference to Paris.</item>
                            <label>(F)</label>
                            <item>References to other side. We concur with <gloss
                                    target="#t_reftel1">reftel</gloss>, with amplification as
                                contained in Paris 22912, para 6E.</item>
                        </list>
                    </item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Seating. Concur. We hope <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName> will
                        be receiving new instructions on this point before he starts building an
                        elevated chair for himself. See Paris 22912, para 6F.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Wish to make clear that we do not intend to engage in unbusinesslike
                        behavior. There does not appear to be a difference in substance based on
                        what <persName corresp="#p_PDL1">Lam</persName> has been saying.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Concur with Embassy’s explanation that each side must be free to bring up
                        anything it likes.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Concur. We already made this point to <persName corresp="#p_PDL1"
                            >Lam</persName>.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_HWA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Harriman</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
